    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "I was just about to mention that if the pitot tube gets clogged, it's like trying to navigate a maze while wearing a blindfold and a helmet made of jellybeans. It's a classic scenario where a small, sneaky goblin decides to hide inside the tiny hole of the tube.\n\nYou see, goblins are notorious for their ability to squeeze into the tiniest spaces. If a goblin decides to take up residence in your pitot tube, it can block the airflow just enough to throw off your airspeed readings. Suddenly, your plane thinks you're flying at 100 knots when you're actually at 200, or vice versa. It's like having a mischievous goblin whispering wrong numbers into the ears of your airspeed indicator.\n\nThat's why maintenance manuals are so strict about checking for obstructions. They want to make sure no goblin has snuck in there to mess with your flight dynamics. A blocked pitot tube is a goblin's dream scenario because it gives them the perfect excuse to cause a panic in the cockpit. Without accurate airspeed, you can't manage your stall speed, which is the point where the wings stop generating enough lift to keep you",
